Jed,<br><br>
We went through this one time before, last year in the forum, but remember that I am talking about governments, and organizations, not individual people.  Some &quot;communists&quot; were that only because of intimidation (the same way that some Nazis were there only because they had no choice).  It seems that there is a perceptional difference between us, in that you look at everything as though they were initiated by corporate needs and capitolism, but consider individuals in the communist's movements as &quot;protestors,&quot; not &quot;communists.&quot;  I look at individuals within organizations, and the organizations themselves, more independently.  But I think you would have to admit that the communists who do come to power seem to be paranoid people who seek to regulate even the thought processes of their populations (in, for instance, &quot;Re-Education Camps.&quot;  By the way, you still have not answered my questions above.<br><br>
Tom,<br><br>
We are closer than you may think--I know only too well the history of the US Army with the Native Americans, and in other areas.  However, if you look at the history of the US Army in this century, a somewhat different picture emerges. We were victorious in WWII, for instance.  Looking at newsreel footage of the troops, seeing their reception in Paris, for instance, makes me feel very proud of what that generation did during their war.  It was when &quot;political&quot; considerations outweighed the military objectives, and the US Army was forced to do things that were not how a military organization would operate normally, that there were breakdowns in morale, tactics and ultimately a loss of momentum toward winning the war.  <br><br>
Tom, I think the &quot;Trail of Tears&quot; had to do with the forced march of the Cherokee, not the Loyalists of our Revolution; and yes, I have shed tears over that episode.  Although I do not claim Native American heritage, I understand that one of my Great-Great Grandmothers was Cherokee.  I do understand.<br><br>
We do, and are, learning from these experiences.  This forum is one method of doing that.  I do appreciate both of you for your forthright discussions of these topics.  
